WEBVTT

00:11.945 --> 00:14.788
Well, after we'd set this thing up, I went off back 
to the Admiralty. And a month or so, I went over to

00:15.328 --> 00:17.250
have a look at it. It was rather like Henry VIII 
visiting Trinity. You know, the founder come to

00:20.834 --> 00:23.336
visit the thing. And the people were all quite 
enthusiastic about it, because they'd otherwise

00:23.356 --> 00:27.880
have been fighting in the Battle of the Bulwark. 
And it was really, really great fun. The first time

00:31.444 --> 00:37.750
I went over, it was foggy and the Air Force couldn't 
take us over. I got on to the operations at Dover and

00:38.371 --> 00:42.318
said, look, can you take us over to France? They 
said, sure. And we were actually the first, we went

00:43.140 --> 00:50.374
over in a motor torpedo boat, and we were the first 
vessel into Boulogne after it was liberated,

00:43.140 --> 00:50.374
after the Germans got out. It was interesting to 
see a place that we were the first people into.

00:56.104 --> 00:58.509
Nothing had been done, just as left by the Germans. 
All the port destroyed, everything blown up. and

01:02.418 --> 01:28.358
then we went back to paris and along the roads of 
course where all the bridges were blown

01:02.418 --> 01:28.358
everything was wrecked and then then we worked our 
way we got into brussels just after it was

01:02.418 --> 01:28.358
liberated wonderful with all the rejoicings of 
the liberation the the capture we were got in just

01:02.418 --> 01:28.358
after the capture of the luftwaffe's wine cellar 
by the second technical air force we did very well

01:02.418 --> 01:28.358
there and then we set up advanced headquarters in 
Berlin. We had all kinds of organizations, really

01:32.536 --> 01:37.500
great fun, and not very serious, of course. Well, 
then when the German war was over, I decided I

01:39.222 --> 01:48.130
really didn't want to sit out the Japanese war as 
well. So I went back to Cambridge in, I think, the

01:48.190 --> 01:53.434
war ended in August. Yes, beginning of July, I went 
back to Cambridge. It obviously wasn't going to be

01:56.917 --> 01:58.699
very long. The last job I did, was it the last? No, it 
was just one interesting thing. It wasn't much to

02:06.189 --> 02:13.356
do with oceanography, but the question was raised 
about a year or 18 months before the end of the war.

02:14.057 --> 02:28.551
The Combined Chiefs of Staff were told to produce a 
plan for defeating Japan within a year of the

02:14.057 --> 02:28.551
defeat of Germany, because it was thought that the 
British and public would not stand the war in Japan

02:28.868 --> 02:35.274
going on for more than a year after the defeat of 
Germany, which seemed quite likely. And everyone

02:36.075 --> 02:41.941
got in on this act in one way or another, 
considering this question. It involved, first of

02:42.001 --> 02:49.448
all, deciding when Germany was going to be 
defeated, and secondly, deciding on a plan for

02:42.001 --> 02:49.448
defeating Japan within a year thereafter. Well, 
it was got completely wrong. It was decided that

02:55.936 --> 02:59.239
Germany would be defeated in the late fall of 44. In 
fact, they lasted six months longer, seven months

02:59.900 --> 03:02.823
longer. And it was decided that Japan could not be 
defeated within a year thereafter. It couldn't be

03:07.787 --> 03:12.572
defeated by the fall of 45. And they were both 
wrong. And it's very interesting, showing with

03:14.394 --> 03:23.783
really very experienced, very intelligent 
people considering these matters, you get it

03:14.394 --> 03:23.783
completely wrong. on the effect of the bombing of 
Japan. I underestimated the effects because I

03:26.334 --> 03:33.264
didn't believe what the Air Force said. In Europe, 
we'd always divided Air Force estimates by pi

03:33.404 --> 03:40.975
because they were always over-optimistic. In 
Japan, Japan was much more inflammable and they

03:41.436 --> 03:49.127
really had done much more damage than the same 
weight of bombs in Europe. We discounted the We

03:51.995 --> 04:04.430
also thought it would take longer to develop 
airfields on the islands when they were captured

03:51.995 --> 04:04.430
than it actually did because it involved 
bulldozing the tops off all the hills to set up

03:51.995 --> 04:04.430
airfields. We discounted the effects of the atom 
bomb because we didn't believe it were ready in

04:04.970 --> 04:09.075
time. We didn't think the first test would work. We 
thought it would all take longer. And so he said for

04:14.902 --> 04:19.167
planning purposes one should not assume it would 
work. So it is a very odd thing and interesting.

04:22.422 --> 04:33.175
It's nothing to do with oceanography, but it's 
interesting how really the best and most careful

04:22.422 --> 04:33.175
consideration by the military experts and their 
civilian advisors arrived at completely wrong

04:22.422 --> 04:33.175
answers. Well, now, we've now reached the end of 
the war. But I have a couple of questions I want to

04:38.261 --> 04:42.426
ask you before we reach totally upon the end.

04:45.890 --> 04:50.115
When you're working in terms of gravity 
experiments on submarines, Was

04:50.500 --> 04:57.130
this involved in warfare? No, not at all. I didn't 
think so. There was no military application at all

04:59.713 --> 05:03.639
at the time. It has certain applications now, but 
that's nothing to do with what we're talking about

05:04.660 --> 05:10.869
now. There are questions of the trajectories of 
ballistic missiles. The calculation of those

05:16.217 --> 05:19.562
involves a knowledge of variations of gravity. 
