05:19.812 --> 05:23.596
application. And when you were in charge of 
degassing in terms of mines, did you not in turn

05:23.616 --> 05:33.047
invent a kind of mine which was much more 
effective? Yes. Where did you hear that? Oh, I

05:34.749 --> 05:36.831
just... Where did you pick that up? Roger Revelle. 
Yes, that's true. This man, Ben Brown, whom I

05:40.395 --> 05:47.003
talked about before as the man who measured 
gravity in submarines, he stayed in the

05:40.395 --> 05:47.003
anti-submarine establishment. He suffered 
fools much more gladly than I did. And he stayed

05:49.613 --> 05:50.534
there. And he and I, between us, I think I 
originally invented it, and he did some

05:51.155 --> 05:56.362
experiments to see whether it was practical. We 
invented a pressure mine, which worked when a ship

05:56.402 --> 06:07.477
goes over an object on the bottom, there is a 
reduction of pressure as it goes over. And we

06:07.497 --> 06:09.440
invented a mine which worked this way. Well, it was 
decided to be too dangerous for us to use it because

06:15.685 --> 06:16.946
we had no means of sweeping it. I put a lot of work 
into developing methods of sweeping with no

06:17.227 --> 06:25.015
success and so it was really a very dangerous thing 
and it was decided not to use it. It was used, the

06:26.277 --> 06:38.770
Germans must have invented it independently, it 
was used right at the end of the war in the Scheldt

06:26.277 --> 06:38.770
Estuary out when they evacuated Holland and it was 
used extensively by the Americans in the last

06:26.277 --> 06:38.770
stages of the Japanese war. Now when you go back I 
don't know whether the American invention was

06:42.601 --> 06:45.765
independent. I think not. Well, my impression is 
it was not. That was a conversation I drew from

06:49.050 --> 06:50.772
Ravel. Well, I think that's only because I told 
Ravel I thought it was not independent. Okay.

