23:02.994 --> 23:09.580
interested in computers, and I was practically 
the only man on the board in anything about them.

23:10.361 --> 23:15.045
It's been suggested that you were in the vanguard 
of placing computers into British science. Would

23:15.085 --> 23:16.947
you agree with that statement? certainly I was one 
of the first people who took them seriously in

23:17.770 --> 23:47.271
geophysics I mean computers are used for two 
things in science one is data analysis if you've

23:17.770 --> 23:47.271
got a subject like astronomy or geophysics where 
there's an enormous amount of information badly

23:17.770 --> 23:47.271
contaminated with noise then you need a computer 
to analyse the data and I was certainly early in

23:17.770 --> 23:47.271
this business I did a lot of the early programming 
for

23:47.555 --> 23:56.505
recording data on board ship and then analyzing it 
after you got home. Now, of course, you do the

23:56.525 --> 24:00.029
analysis as well at sea because you have the 
computers at sea. But at that time, the computers

24:00.089 --> 24:06.257
were on land and you brought the data back on paper 
tape and put it into the computers. And I did a lot of

24:06.297 --> 24:11.883
programming and experimental work on data 
analysis in oceanography.

24:15.828 --> 24:17.089
This I... when I got back to Cambridge, I used to 
visit here in the summer from the late 50s onwards.

24:25.292 --> 24:36.487
And I worked here with Walter Monk and Flicka down 
the corridor, Flicka Dolma, Flicka Oglebay as it

24:25.292 --> 24:36.487
was, on general programs for analyzing data. So I 
think I did have substantial influence on the

24:37.268 --> 24:45.379
adoption of computers for data analysis in 
geophysics. And the other side of the use of

24:48.963 --> 24:53.308
computers in science is their use for analyzing 
models. If you have a phenomenon, say an ice age or a

24:53.809 --> 25:03.200
tsunami or something of this sort, or the tides, 
then you have a theory of it. And your theory is a

25:03.821 --> 25:07.165
simplified model of reality. And you want to 
predict what this model will say about the

25:07.766 --> 25:14.734
observations, about what should happen, and then 
compare what actually happens and what the theory

25:14.883 --> 25:17.246
gives. And this is quite a different sort of 
computing. It's solving differential equations

25:19.850 --> 25:21.913
and things. And I haven't... I did some of this in 
the magnetic field business, the origin of the

25:24.596 --> 25:30.945
Earth's magnetic field. And so that I think on both 
sides I did something. I was in that when I was at the

25:35.331 --> 25:38.295
National Physical Lab. I started doing that. 
Being director of the lab, I could get as much

25:40.178 --> 25:43.422
computer time as I wanted... The National 
Physical Lab, though, was not defense-oriented,

25:44.566 --> 25:47.349
was it? No. Okay, I don't think so. No, it was 
industry-oriented. It was particularly

25:52.295 --> 25:53.356
standards. When did you first become interested 
in heat flow? I first became interested in heat

25:59.804 --> 26:03.408
flow in the middle 30s. I remember talking to 
Jeffries about it. I was interested... I think my

26:13.203 --> 26:20.670
first interest was how reliable were the few 
measurements we had. Wait a minute now, now my

26:21.331 --> 26:30.379
first interest, Jeffries talked to me about the 
shortage of heat flow measurements, there were

26:21.331 --> 26:30.379
very few. I wrote a historical article on the 
history of heat flow measurement. What had

26:37.927 --> 26:39.328
happened was,

26:45.805 --> 26:53.816
I've become, well, I think to go into the details of 
Mr. Lee is really rather unnecessary, but Mr. Lee

26:45.805 --> 26:53.816
was a graduate student here. And for reasons that 
are too complicated to describe, I got him made

26:54.897 --> 27:04.410
Secretary of the International Keep Flow 
Committee when he was about 22 or 23, I suppose.

27:04.891 --> 27:08.356
Enormously energetic man, determined to make his 
fortune, his fame and fortune. And one of the

27:08.997 --> 27:13.703
things he did was to start to get a collaborative 
book written about heat flow from the earth to be

27:14.527 --> 27:21.996
published by his international heat flow 
committee. And he asked me to write a summarizing

27:22.016 --> 27:24.980
chapter. And I refused to do it on the grounds that I 
couldn't be bothered to read all the manuscripts

27:25.660 --> 27:29.765
he'd got. And he wrote to me a very fierce letter in 
which he said he thought this was very

27:30.566 --> 27:34.371
unreasonable. I just must write him an article. He 
was clearly one of these people like Dick Field who

27:35.712 --> 27:38.796
wouldn't take no for an answer. So I said I would 
write him an article on the history of heat flow.

27:43.075 --> 27:51.545
This was intended originally more or less a joke, 
and I started to write a history of heat flow in the

27:43.075 --> 27:51.545
17th century. And so I wrote an article on the study 
of heat flow from the Earth in the 17th century,

27:52.406 --> 27:57.973
which is rather surprising. Boyle was interested 
in it. And then I decided to write this more

28:01.797 --> 28:07.264
seriously, and I continued it up to the present 
day. And I haven't got a copy of this here, I'm

28:07.666 --> 28:09.788
afraid. But anyway, in the middle 30s, I'd become 
interested in it. This was in the 50s sometime. I'd

28:17.955 --> 28:20.237
become interested in the thing in the 30s. Of 
course, Jeffries had pointed out how few

28:20.257 --> 28:23.220
measurements there were. And I'd put a graduate 
student onto it in about 36 or 37. And he was making

28:28.164 --> 28:34.369
measurements in England in collaboration with 
the oil companies who got some boreholes. And I did

28:35.150 --> 28:37.352
some measurements in South Africa. And so I then 
became, I became interested in the whole

28:37.838 --> 28:42.924
question, how do you measure heat flow? How, what 
sources of uncertainty are there? I became

28:46.688 --> 28:51.093
interested in the effect of the topography of the 
earth and distorting the heat flow and so on. And I

28:51.694 --> 28:57.381
then also became interested just before the war in 
the possibility of making measurements at sea.

28:57.401 --> 28:58.923
And at that time, war was on us. I didn't get 
anything done before the war. Then, after the war,

29:02.647 --> 29:07.052
I tried to get Maurice Ewing interested. And 
Morris Ewing had his own problems and couldn't

29:08.112 --> 29:10.995
give me ship time. And eventually Roger Revelle 
offered me ship time. But then when I got down here,

29:14.919 --> 29:18.863
he wouldn't give me any workshop time. I think very 
foolishly. And so Art Maxwell and I went into the

29:20.324 --> 29:26.210
workshop here and started to build the equipment. 
And I was very surprised that the workshop

29:26.230 --> 29:32.076
manager, the head mechanic, wouldn't let us into 
the store. And I thought this was very odd. It

29:35.420 --> 29:37.782
turned out afterwards that there was a racket 
going on. He was buying stores and running a shop in

29:38.335 --> 29:44.465
town and selling them again. And, of course, we 
were very liable to discover this racket, that he

29:44.505 --> 29:52.699
was taking things away in the evening, because we 
were staying much later than he was. So it must have

29:53.841 --> 29:55.464
been a grave embarrassment to him. And shortly 
after we left, this all came out.

